  "nid": "1_95",
  "title": "Respiratory physiology: PEFR & FEV1/FVC Ratio",
  "body_html": "<b>Peak expiratory flow rate</b><br />Peak expiratory flow rate (PEFR) is a useful test that measures a patient's maximum speed of expiration. It is usually quick and easy to perform. Expected PEFR varies depending on age, sex and height. <br /><br />PEFR is dependent on initial lung volumes and patient effort. PEFR decreases when airways resistance is increased. <br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti464b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti464.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>PEFR charts showing normal expected values dependent on age, sex and height</div><br /><b>Spirometry</b><br />Spirometry provides more information than PEFR and measures the volume of air expired over time. The FEV1 and FVC are perhaps the most important values obtained and are used in the diagnosis of obstructive and restrictive lung diseases. <br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti465b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti465.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Illustration showing variation in patterns of FEV1 and FVC in obstructive and restrictive lung disease</div><br /><b>Forced vital capacity (FVC)</b><br />The FVC is the maximum volume of air that can be expelled from the lungs after maximum inspiration. In restrictive lung disease the FVC is reduced as the lung volume is reduced. The FVC may be normal or reduced in obstructive lung disease.<br /><br /><b>Forced expiratory volume (FEV)</b><br />The FEV1 measures the maximum amount of air a patient can exhale in the first second of expiration following maximum inspiration<br /><br /><b>Interpretation of results</b><br /><br /><br /><div class='alert alert-warning'>NICE consider a FEV1/FVC ratio of less than 70% (0.7) consistent with obstructive lung disease (asthma and COPD)<br /><br />Normal FEV1 and FVC are >80% predicted. Normal FEV1/FVC is 0.75-0.85<br /></div><br /><br /><div class=\"table-responsive\"><table class = \"tlarge table table-striped table-bordered\"  data-role=\"table\" id=\"tableid1\" ><thead><tr><th></th><th>Obstructive</th><th>Restrictive</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>FEV1</td><td>Low</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>FVC</td><td>Normal or low</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>FEV1/FVC</td><td>Low</td><td>Normal or high</td></tr><tr><td>PEFR</td><td>Low</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>Example causes</td><td>Asthma<br />COPD</td><td>Pulmonary fibrosis (any cause)<br />Sarcoidosis<br />Obesity<br />Neuromuscular disease<br />Atelectasis<br />Pneumonia<br />Pulmonary effusion<br />Pulmonary oedema</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>NICE</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_323\" data-linkid=\"323\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_323\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">2</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_323\" data-linkid=\"323\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_323\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng115/chapter/Recommendations#diagnosing-copd\">Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease in over 16s: diagnosis and management</a></td></tr></table><br><br><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>ncbi</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_329\" data-linkid=\"329\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_329\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">1</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_329\" data-linkid=\"329\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_329\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493170/\">Physiology, Residual Volume</a></td></tr></table><br><br><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>BMJ</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_328\" data-linkid=\"328\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_328\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">0</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_328\" data-linkid=\"328\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_328\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://thorax.bmj.com/content/thoraxjnl/40/1/60.full.pdf\">Effects-of pneumothorax or pleural effusion on pulmonary function</a></td></tr></table><br><br><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>NICE</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_324\" data-linkid=\"324\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_324\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">0</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_324\" data-linkid=\"324\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_324\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng80/chapter/Recommendations#objective-tests-for-diagnosing-asthma-in-adults-young-people-and-children-aged-5-and-over\">Asthma: diagnosis, monitoring and chronic asthma management</a></td></tr></table></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">2</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">6</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Physiology</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Respiratory physiology</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\n<b>Peak expiratory flow rate</b><br />Peak expiratory flow rate (PEFR) is a useful test that measures a patient's maximum speed of expiration. It is usually quick and easy to perform. Expected PEFR varies depending on age, sex and height. <br /><br />PEFR is dependent on initial lung volumes and patient effort. PEFR decreases when airways resistance is increased. <br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti464b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti464.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>PEFR charts showing normal expected values dependent on age, sex and height</div><br /><b>Spirometry</b><br />Spirometry provides more information than PEFR and measures the volume of air expired over time. The FEV1 and FVC are perhaps the most important values obtained and are used in the diagnosis of obstructive and restrictive lung diseases. <br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti465b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti465.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Illustration showing variation in patterns of FEV1 and FVC in obstructive and restrictive lung disease</div><br /><b>Forced vital capacity (FVC)</b><br />The FVC is the maximum volume of air that can be expelled from the lungs after maximum inspiration. In restrictive lung disease the FVC is reduced as the lung volume is reduced. The FVC may be normal or reduced in obstructive lung disease.<br /><br /><b>Forced expiratory volume (FEV)</b><br />The FEV1 measures the maximum amount of air a patient can exhale in the first second of expiration following maximum inspiration<br /><br /><b>Interpretation of results</b><br /><br /><br /><div class='alert alert-warning'>NICE consider a FEV1/FVC ratio of less than 70% (0.7) consistent with obstructive lung disease (asthma and COPD)<br /><br />Normal FEV1 and FVC are >80% predicted. Normal FEV1/FVC is 0.75-0.85<br /></div><br /><br /><div class=\"table-responsive\"><table class = \"tlarge table table-striped table-bordered\"  data-role=\"table\" id=\"tableid1\" ><thead><tr><th></th><th>Obstructive</th><th>Restrictive</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>FEV1</td><td>Low</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>FVC</td><td>Normal or low</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>FEV1/FVC</td><td>Low</td><td>Normal or high</td></tr><tr><td>PEFR</td><td>Low</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>Example causes</td><td>Asthma<br />COPD</td><td>Pulmonary fibrosis (any cause)<br />Sarcoidosis<br />Obesity<br />Neuromuscular disease<br />Atelectasis<br />Pneumonia<br />Pulmonary effusion<br />Pulmonary oedema</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>\n\n\n<BR><BR><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>NICE</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_323\" data-linkid=\"323\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_323\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">2</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_323\" data-linkid=\"323\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_323\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng115/chapter/Recommendations#diagnosing-copd\">Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease in over 16s: diagnosis and management</a></td></tr></table><br><br><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>ncbi</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_329\" data-linkid=\"329\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_329\"